      <body>
         <div>
            <head>Translated parts</head>
            <p xml:id="CH2b1913-start">
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.3" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:00:18.319+09:00">tr. Joseph Roe Allen: Literature</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.4" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:05:29.735+09:00">is used to promulgate the phenomena of superior and inferior.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.5" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:05:46.791+09:00">to clarify the proper order in human relationships,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.6" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:06:37.36+09:00">and to delve deeply into principles and express one's emotions.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.8" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:11:18.667+09:00">When the royal benefices flow, Poetry is made;</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.9" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:11:49.92+09:00">when accomplishments are outstanding, Laudations arise;</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.10" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:12:25.819+09:00">when virtuous merit is established Inscriptions are composed;</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.11" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:12:58.132+09:00">when the good and magnificent men die Elegies accumulate.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.12" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:13:41.623+09:00">As the Officer of the Sarifice presents the litany,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.13" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:14:16.946+09:00">the official admonishes the king for his deficiencies.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.14" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:15:00.057+09:00">In the Rites of Zhou the grand Music Master</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.16" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:18:18.489+09:00">These are called Aria Narratio, Comparatio, Elicio, Elegantia, and Laudatio.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.17" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:21:15.106+09:00">If it spoke about the affairs of a single state</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.18" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:23:27.625+09:00">or was concerned with the situation of an individual</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.19" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:23:47.422+09:00">then it was called an Aria.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.20" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:33:00.58+09:00">If it spoke aobut the affairs of the whole world</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.21" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:33:15.03+09:00">or described the practices within the four quarters of the world,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.22" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:33:23.931+09:00">it was called an Elegantia.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.23" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:33:38.168+09:00">The Laudatio</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.24" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:34:00.431+09:00">was the manifestationof the countenance of great virtue.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.25" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:34:07.145+09:00">The Narratio</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.26" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:34:23.388+09:00">was the term for description and display,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.27" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:34:35.761+09:00">while the Comparatio</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.28" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:34:44.749+09:00">was the language for making comparisons.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.29" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:34:53.233+09:00">And the Elicio</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.30" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:35:17.156+09:00">was the language for evoking sentiments.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.31" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:36:03.988+09:00">In the subseuqent ages there were many who composed poetry,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.32" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:36:28.875+09:00">and if theses pieces dealt with merit and virtue they were called Laudatio.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.33" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:36:47.831+09:00">The remainder of the works were collectively called poetry.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.34" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:36:59.961+09:00">Thus, Laudatios</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.35" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:37:08.414+09:00">were the fines pieces of poetry.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.36" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:37:28.263+09:00">When the sagacious emperor or enlightened king of antiquity</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.37" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:41:48.654+09:00">                                    established his merit and stabilised his rule</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.38" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:38:14.376+09:00">then there arose the music of the Laudatio.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.39" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:42:01.893+09:00">                                    Thereupon the scribes would record these pieces</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.40" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:38:53.393+09:00">and the musicians would put these to music</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.41" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:39:03.811+09:00">and present them in the Ancestral Temple,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.42" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:39:32.005+09:00">making pronouncements  tot he departed spirits and the deities.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.43" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T17:40:33.082+09:00">Thus, what the Laudatio praised</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.44" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T23:44:34.276+09:00">                                    was the virtue of the Sagacious king.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.45" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:10:47.447+09:00">Then, later, based on these ancient pieces, they constructed the pitch pipes,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.46" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:11:27.932+09:00">and in their compositions they would sometimes use the form of the Laudatio</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.47" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:11:42.697+09:00">and sometimes its music.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.48" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:12:16.688+09:00">And although these compositions might be exacting in form and sound</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.49" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:12:53.866+09:00">they did not harbor the same meaning of the Laudatio of old.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.50" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:13:59.503+09:00">Formerly, Ban Gu composed the "Laudatio for Marquis Dai of Anfeng"</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.51" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:15:48.095+09:00">and Sh Cen composed the</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.52" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:15:50.156+09:00">"Laudatio for Empress Deng the harmonious Light,"</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.53" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:16:24.285+09:00">and though they be similar in form to the "Laudatios of Lu"</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.54" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:16:48.71+09:00">the difference in language</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.56" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:19:30.82+09:00">Yang Xiong's "Laudatio for Zhao Chongguo"</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.57" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:19:47.493+09:00">is called a Laudatio,, yet it is similar to an Elegantia.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.58" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:20:10.275+09:00">Fu Yi's "Laudatio for Xianzong</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.59" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:20:31.685+09:00">in language es similar to the "Laudatios of Zhou"</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.60" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:20:50.945+09:00">yet it has a mixture of the meanings of the Aria and Elegantia.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.61" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:21:21.925+09:00">Ma Rong's composition of "Kuangcheng" and "Shanglin"</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.62" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:21:41.246+09:00">are completely in the form of the present-day Narratio,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.63" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:23:36.01+09:00">                                    and yet they are called Laudatios.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.2" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:31:01.726+09:00">The Narratio,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.3" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:31:10.043+09:00">as description and display,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.5" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:36:08.895+09:00">The poets of antiquity</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.6" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:36:43.974+09:00">received their inspiration from emotion</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.7" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:42:46.775+09:00">and the theme of their work ended in propriety and righteousness.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.8" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:43:17.783+09:00">Their inspiration from emotion</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.9" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:44:10.447+09:00">was described by the use of language,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.10" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:44:43.228+09:00">and the theme of propriety</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.11" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:44:56.124+09:00">and righteousness clarified by employing facts</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.12" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:45:46.213+09:00">Thus here we have the narratio</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.13" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:46:22.552+09:00">that, by creating images, taxes the extreme</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.14" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:46:33.941+09:00">to describe and display its intent.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.15" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:46:55.554+09:00">In former times,, of those who composed Narratios,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.16" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:47:29.061+09:00">Sun Qing and Qu Yuan</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.17" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:47:48.966+09:00">had to a certain degree the righeousness of ancient poetry.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.18" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:48:32.398+09:00">Song Yu, however, was afflicted by a certain amount of excessiveness.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.19" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:49:34.875+09:00">The Narrations of the Chuci</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.20" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:50:29.631+09:00">are the finest of the Narratios.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.21" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T19:52:16.754+09:00">Therefore, Yang Xiong has said, "In the genre of Narratio there is none so profound as the 'Lisao""</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.22" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T20:03:11.99+09:00">And the works of Jia Yi</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.23" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T20:04:38.065+09:00">are companion pieces to those of Qu Yuan.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.24" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T20:04:50.514+09:00">The Narratio of ancient poetry</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.25" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-20T20:05:09.74+09:00">gives priary importance to emotion and righetousness</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.27" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:24:40.127+09:00">The Narratio of the present, however,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.28" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:24:52.916+09:00">takes fat and form as basic</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.29" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:25:24.246+09:00">and righteousness and correctness as supplemental.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.30" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:25:43.33+09:00">When emotion and rigtheousness are of primary importance,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.31" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:26:03.57+09:00">then the language is simple and the literature possesses a sense of regulation.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.32" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:26:19.351+09:00">But if fact and form are consdiered basic, then</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.33" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:26:41.194+09:00">then though the language be appropriate, the rhetoric has no consistency.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.34" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:27:07.767+09:00">This is probaly from whence come the simplicity and coplexity</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.35" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:27:57.665+09:00">If the images one creates are excessive,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.36" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:28:27.771+09:00">then the comparisons become too strained to be effective.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.37" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:28:46.996+09:00">If one's lofty diction is too vigorous</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.38" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:29:06.473+09:00">then it becomes divorced from reality.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.39" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:29:33.898+09:00">If in argument one is too logical,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.40" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:29:48.77+09:00">then the meaning of it is lost.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.41" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:33:28.229+09:00">If in argument one is too logical</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.42" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:31:02.595+09:00">then it defies true emotion.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.43" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:48:32.334+09:00">                                    If in elegance and charisma one's writign is too beautiful</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.47" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:47:01.626+09:00">                                    And it is because of this that Sima Qian edited out Sima Xiangru's frivolous language,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.48" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:47:04.742+09:00">                                    and Yang Xiong was distressed with the Narratio of poetasters who were elegant so much as to be licentious.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.49" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:35:25.733+09:00"/>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.2" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:35:54.835+09:00">The Book of Documents says,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.3" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:36:04.147+09:00">"Poetry speaks of intention,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.4" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:36:24.921+09:00">and songs intone the words."</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.5" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:36:49.917+09:00">When it speaks of intention it is called poetry.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.6" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:37:04.66+09:00">In antiquity there was the Poetry Collection Office,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.7" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:37:47.6+09:00">and it was by this that the king  came to know the successes and failures of his rule.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.8" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:38:00.996+09:00">The Poetry of antiquity</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.9" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:38:24.949+09:00">was composed in lines of three, four, five, six, seven, and nine syllables.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.10" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:38:55.884+09:00">Ancient Poetry generally employed the four-syllable line as its basic form,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.11" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:39:17.392+09:00">yet occasionally there was n odd line or two mixed in with the four-lyllable lines.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.12" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:39:34.185+09:00">Later generations expanded these odd lines</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.13" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:39:52.027+09:00">to make complete compositions.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.14" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:40:07.05+09:00">Of the three-syllable lines of ancient Poetry,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.55" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:42:57.024+09:00">CH: is a matter of historical development</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.4" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T23:29:53.507+09:00">belongs to the tradition of old Poetry.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.26" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T23:45:12.576+09:00">CH the catalogue of matters was secondary.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.45" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:46:55.275+09:00">Yielding to these four excesses</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.46" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:46:58.695+09:00">is how one comes to turn his back on the on the great principles and harms both government and culture.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-37a.44" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:48:44.399+09:00">then it defies true emotion.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.15" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:51:04.021+09:00">the lines "Flocking flocking egrets,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.16" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:51:32.013+09:00">egrets in flight" are an example of this type.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.17" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:52:12.739+09:00">During the Han dynasty hymns of sacrifice and temple often used this type of line.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.18" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:52:56.265+09:00">Of the five-syllable lines,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.19" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:53:14.423+09:00">the lines "Who says the sparrow has to eak?</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.20" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T00:53:56.588+09:00">With what then does he pierce my roof?" are an example.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.21" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T17:37:12.909+09:00">Comic verse and entertainment songs also use this type of line.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.22" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T17:38:18.065+09:00">Of the six-syllable lines</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.23" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T17:38:43.847+09:00">the line "For the moment I pour from that bronze wine jar," is an example.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.24" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T17:39:30.049+09:00">the yuefu ballads also use this type of line.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.25" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T17:40:08.373+09:00">Of the seven-syllable lines ,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.26" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T17:40:23.106+09:00">the line "To and fro flies the oriole, It lights on the bulberry tree" is an example.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.27" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T17:40:39.381+09:00">Comic verse and entertainment songs also use this type of line.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.28" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T17:41:14.081+09:00">Of the nine-syllable lines of ancient Poetry</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.29" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T17:41:52.203+09:00">an example is the line "Afar we draw water from the roadside pool, Ladle it up there and pour it out here."</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.30" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T17:42:10.948+09:00">As it cannot be comfortably incorporated into songs,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.31" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T17:42:24.948+09:00">this type of line is rarely used anymore.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.32" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T17:42:46.176+09:00">Although Poetry makes emotion and intention its basis</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.33" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T17:42:57.914+09:00">it is regulated by a set cadence.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.34" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T17:43:14.181+09:00">Thus the metrics of elegant music</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.35" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T17:43:26.369+09:00">are correct for the four-syllable line</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.36" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T17:44:09.947+09:00">and the other types of line, although they offer an alternate form</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.37" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T17:44:45.938+09:00">they are not musically correct</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-38a.38" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T17:45:04.981+09:00"/>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.2" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T18:33:03.258+09:00">The "Seven Stimuli" was written be Mei Sheng,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.3" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T18:33:25.28+09:00">and it has a guest from Wu and a lord from Chu as its principal characters.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.4" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T18:34:13.213+09:00">First it speaks of the weakness of rheumatism and paralysis resulting from riding a coach outside the palace</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.5" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T18:35:13.29+09:00">and the affliction of chills and sweats from frquenting the inner palace and chambers.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.6" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T18:35:39.764+09:00">And it speaks also of the posoning effect of sexual indulgence and easy living,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.7" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T18:36:04.945+09:00">and the harm caused by excessive use of rich foods and warm clothes.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.8" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T20:56:38.59+09:00">                                    It also notes that one should heed the esse3ntial words and marvelous doctrines of the wise men of the ages,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.9" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T20:57:41.85+09:00">and in this way one would channel his spirit</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.10" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T20:58:09.733+09:00">and direct himself away from the trouble caused by these pleasures.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.11" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T20:58:31.467+09:00">Having set forth these words</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.12" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T20:58:49.045+09:00">that clearly outline the road one should take toward recovery,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.13" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T20:59:12.137+09:00">the poem then argues over the pleasures of women, music, leisure, and travel;</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.14" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T20:59:22.768+09:00">but the arguments have no effect.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.15" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T20:59:47.417+09:00">Then the poem shows the delight to be found in the explanations and discussion of sages and debaters.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.16" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T21:00:02.052+09:00">With this the illness is suddenly cured.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.17" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T21:00:41.14+09:00">Thus, this is understood as one curative advice for that illness commonly suffered by those who live the life of ease.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.18" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T21:00:59.157+09:00">And although the piece uses exaggerated language</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.19" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T21:01:29.324+09:00">it has yet to lose the principle of instructing by indirect criticism.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.20" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T21:01:52.892+09:00">The development of this type of writing was broad,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.21" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T21:02:02.797+09:00">thus its principles changed</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.22" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T21:02:40.903+09:00">yet the later pieces generally are burdened with that frivolous elegance peculiar to poetasters.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.23" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T21:02:58.006+09:00">Cui Yin, after writing the "Seven Dependencies"</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.24" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T21:03:31.569+09:00">a piece of this sort, said in the words of a fictional characgter,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.25" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T21:03:41.526+09:00">"Alas!"</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.26" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T21:03:52.682+09:00">Yang Xiong has said,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.27" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T21:04:10.392+09:00">The young boy wastges his time carving elegant phrases,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.28" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T21:04:20.819+09:00">then abruptly says,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.29" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T21:05:24.426+09:00">Confucius was distressed by the way petty language could destroy the True Way.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.30" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T21:05:44.49+09:00">How could one possibly contend that this type of writing</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.31" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T21:06:07.621+09:00">is adequate in meaning, and not overwrought in eloquence?</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.32" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T21:06:27.082+09:00">The Narratio is supposed to criticize indirectly,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.33" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T21:06:54.319+09:00">yet I fear thee pieces are no more than mere advice.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-39a.34" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T21:06:58.273+09:00"/>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.2" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T23:31:24.956+09:00">                                    Yang Xiong wrote his twelve prefectural and twelve official administments based on the "Forester's Admonishment" and they have come down to our age.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-36a.64" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T23:29:57.967+09:00">CH: This is far from right.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.3" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T23:33:12.374+09:00">But since these did not cover all nine offices,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.4" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T23:33:33.226+09:00">Cui Yin in the following age filled the deficiencies in his works.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.5" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T23:34:09.106+09:00">Hu Guang then arranged the order of the works and wrote a commentary for them.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.6" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T23:34:41.51+09:00">This compilation is called the Admonishments of the Various Officials.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.7" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T23:34:41.704+09:00"/>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.8" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T23:35:06.075+09:00">The inscriptions of antiquity were extremely laconic</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.9" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T23:35:23.341+09:00">and those of the present day are extremely prolix,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.10" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T23:35:31.459+09:00">and yet there is a reason for this.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.11" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T23:36:40.728+09:00">the changes that take place in the simplicity and complexity of literature through time</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.12" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T23:36:48.231+09:00">In fact we have already discussed.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.13" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T23:37:23.73+09:00">The inscriptions of high antiquity</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.15" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T23:38:01.978+09:00">When Cai Yong made an Inscription on the tablet for Duke Yang,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.16" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T23:38:10.668+09:00">his writing was classic and correct,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.17" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T23:38:27.256+09:00">and it was the best work in the declining years of the Han dynasty.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.18" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T23:39:15.34+09:00">Among the fines Inscriptions on utensils found in the latter years</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.19" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T23:40:28.484+09:00">are Wang Mang's "Cauldron Inscription," Cui Yuan's "Stool Inscription, Zhu Gongshu's "Cauldron Inscription" and Wang Can's "inkstone Inscription"</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.20" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T23:41:05.868+09:00">All of these were made to describe moritorious virtue.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.21" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T23:41:45.245+09:00">The imperial Inscriptions of former ages were made on the Jialiang standard,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.22" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T23:42:15.12+09:00">and those of the lords and ministers were made on the Taichang standard,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.23" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T23:42:22.817+09:00">bells and cauldrons.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.24" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T23:42:47.466+09:00">And although what they say may be different,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.25" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-21T23:43:10.188+09:00">in principle, the excellent virtue of which they speak is one and the same.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.26" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:39:59.266+09:00">Li You's Inscriptions</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.14" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:38:45.08+09:00">were inscribed upon the tablets of the ancestral temple.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.27" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:41:02.25+09:00">include those for mountains, rivers, capitals, and cities;</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.28" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:41:38.285+09:00">he even made them for knives, brushes, paper weight and inscribing blades.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.29" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:41:51.249+09:00">In all these he had Inscriptions.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.30" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:42:12.547+09:00">And though his writing form was often ugly and weak</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.31" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:42:28.972+09:00">the texts were polished</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.32" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:42:37.926+09:00">and the words worth recording.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-40a.33" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:42:38.191+09:00"/>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-41a.2" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:43:07.997+09:00">The writings of Poetry, Laudatios, Admonistions, and Inscriptions</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-41a.3" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:43:24.046+09:00">all have texts written in the past</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-41a.4" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:43:41.091+09:00">that can be used as models for the ones composed later.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-41a.5" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:43:57.56+09:00">It is only Elegies that have no established form</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-41a.6" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:44:15.032+09:00">resulting in a great amount of variation among writers.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-41a.7" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:44:36.925+09:00">Of the ones that do appear in the classical texts</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-41a.8" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:45:25.471+09:00">there is the Elegy in the Zuozhuan written for Confucius by Duke Ai of Lu.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-41a.9" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:45:25.734+09:00"/>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-41a.10" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:46:01.046+09:00">The Lament</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-41a.11" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:46:36.133+09:00"> is in the same vein as the Elegy.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-41a.12" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:46:36.777+09:00">Cui Yuan, Su Shun, Ma Rong, and the like are the leading writers of these.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-41a.13" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:47:37.718+09:00">They are pieces written for boys who die young, those whom Heaven strikes down before they reach old age.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-41a.14" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:48:20.418+09:00">During the Jian'an period</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-41a.15" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:48:48.789+09:00">Emperor Wen and the Marquis of Linzi each lost a young child</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-41a.16" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:49:09.548+09:00">and the asked Xu Gan and Liu Chen to write a Lament for them.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-41a.17" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:50:08.884+09:00">The form of the Lament</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-41a.18" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:50:09.344+09:00">takes grief and sorrow as primary</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-41a.19" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:50:10.421+09:00">and embellishes it with the language of sighs.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-42a.2" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:51:38.595+09:00">That which comes down to us now as the Lamentaion is</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-42a.3" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:51:52.102+09:00">is, in principle the same as the ancient Elegy.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-42a.4" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:51:59.279+09:00"/>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-42a.5" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:52:43.897+09:00">The magnanimous breadth of "A Defense" is superior and great.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-42a.6" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:53:02.323+09:00">The profound goodness of the "Response to a Guest" is gentle and elegant.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-42a.7" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:53:31.814+09:00">The vigor of the "United Intent" is ardent,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-42a.8" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:54:09.944+09:00">and the delicacy of "Response to Chiding" is finely distinguished.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-42a.9" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:54:39.599+09:00">In their ornament and refinement</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-42a.10" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:55:00.068+09:00">there is none among them that is not good.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-43a.2" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:55:23.385+09:00">In antiquity there was the tablet of the ancestral tempole</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-43a.3" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:55:38.891+09:00">but in later ages they set the tablet at the tomb,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-43a.4" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:55:54.594+09:00">thereby displaying it to the passing road.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-43a.5" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:56:44.557+09:00">That which we have recorded there are the texts of the Inscription.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-43a.6" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:57:08.481+09:00">The script used in writing books of dynstic prophesy</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-43a.7" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:57:25.724+09:00">are not of the orthodox style</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-43a.8" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T01:58:16.073+09:00">yet from its vertical and horizontal lines one can obtain a meaning,</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-43a.9" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T02:00:05.746+09:00">and from it back and forth ?ign comes a pattern.</seg>
               <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_077-43a.10" xml:lang="en" resp="CH" modified="2019-10-22T02:01:19.609+09:00">Parerga 3. Two Studies in Chinese Literary Criticism, Institute for Comparative and Foreign Area Studies, University of Washington, Seattle, 1976</seg>
            <seg corresp="#CH2b1913_CHANT_127-16a.253" xml:lang="en" resp="#chris" modified="2020-03-24T15:19:10.603+09:00"/>
